; COMMENTS
; Cessna 172 Simplified Configuration
; Realistic small aircraft with essential antennas only
; HF wire antenna + VHF COM antenna (typical GA setup)
;
; Key Configuration:
; 1. HF wire antenna (W028/W029): Wing-tip to fuselage wire - ACTIVE
; 2. VHF COM antenna (W030): 0.5m blade on wing strut - ACTIVE
;
; HF Wire Antenna (W028/W029) Details:
; - Total length: 10.6m (wing tip to wing tip via fuselage)
; - Frequency: 3-30 MHz HF band
; - Feed: Center segment of port side wire (segment 6 of 11)
; - Type: Long wire antenna (efficient for HF)
; - Mounting: Wing tip to fuselage to wing tip
;
; VHF COM Antenna (W030) Details:
; - Position: Port wing strut (-0.8m, -1.2m, 1.3m to 1.8m)
; - Type: 0.5m blade antenna (quarter-wave at 150 MHz)
; - Frequency: 118-136.975 MHz aviation VHF COM band
; - Feed: Center-fed monopole (segment 5 of 10)
; - Mounting: Wing strut position (common GA installation)
;
; Simplified Configuration Benefits:
; - Reduced complexity for typical GA operations
; - Only essential antennas for communication
; - Lower weight and installation complexity
; - Easier maintenance and troubleshooting
; - Cost-effective for small aircraft
;
; Expected Performance:
; - HF: Good efficiency on 3-30 MHz (long wire advantage)
; - VHF: 0 to +4 dBi gain (typical GA performance)
; - Pattern: Directional due to wing strut mounting
; - SWR: <2:1 across respective bands
; - Polarization: Vertical for both antennas
;
; General Aviation Scenario:
; - HF for long-range communication (emergency, amateur)
; - VHF COM for ATC communication (required)
; - Both systems can be active simultaneously
; - Realistic antenna interaction in small aircraft
; - High-wing design provides good ground plane
;
; This simplified model represents a typical general aviation
; aircraft with only the essential antennas for communication,
; removing the excessive HF installations found in the original
; model while maintaining realistic antenna performance.
